                    <lb n="1"/>//ΕΤΕΙΜΗΚΤΤΟΝΠΔΡΙ////ΞΟ/// ATΤIΚΑΙΣ
                    <lb n="2"/>ΠΕΝΤΑΚOΣ<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <div type="commentary" subtype="section" n="1">
                    <ab>Perhaps <w lemma="μή">μή</w> followed by a command now lost, unless it refers to the next line, separated from it by a horizontal rule.
                    </ab>
                </div> 
            <div type="translation">
                <ab/>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary"> 
                <p /> 
            </div>
                <div type="commentary" subtype="section" n="1">
                    <ab>Can this be <w lemma="πολάζω">πολάζῃ</w>, from <w lemma="πολάζω">πολάζω</w>, cited once in LSJ Addenda with the meaning “to be common, abound”?
                </ab>
                </div>
                <div type="commentary" subtype="section" n="3">
                    <ab>If there is not text lost, one can readily understand <w lemma="ἀττικός">Ἀττικαῖς</w> (<w lemma="δραχμή">δραχμαῖς</w>) <w lemma="πεντακοσίος">πεντακοσ[ίαις</w>, 500 Attic drachmas (= denarii). At the beginning, probably a form of <w lemma="τιμάω">τιμάω</w>, either (as Angelos Chaniotis suggests) <w lemma="τιμάω">τετείμηκε</w>, or (as Thomas Corsten would prefer) <w lemma="τιμάω">ἐτείμησε</w>, followed by <w lemma="ὁ">τόν</w>. What follows that escapes us.
                    </ab>
                </div>
            </div>
